If you want to avoid the the “Matches: 0” case, you can add a C condition **on top of using ngettext**, with an additional string. Something along the lines of:

```C
if (matches < 0) {
  text = g_strdup_printf (ngettext ("1 match", "%u matches", matches), matches);
} else {
  text = g_strdup_printf (_("No matches"), matches);
}
```

I also noticed that you have a mix of `ngettext` and `g_dngettext` across the code base, sometimes even within the same file. I’m fairly certain all you need is `ngettext` in your situation.

This is the code causing the loop, added with 3d3c0ae94ee09759beed9cc6248f2b41069e0020:

```c
fallback:

	if (!content || !*content) {
		g_free (content);
		if (is_primary_paste)
			e_content_editor_emit_paste_primary_clipboard (E_CONTENT_EDITOR (wk_editor));
		else
			e_content_editor_emit_paste_clipboard (E_CONTENT_EDITOR (wk_editor));
		return;
	}
```

I think it's attempting to restart the entire paste if there are no compatible targets, or the target it found is empty.

The code in the message composer also looks weird:

```c
	/* Order is important here to ensure common use cases are
	 * handled correctly.  See GNOME bug #603715 for details. */
	if (gtk_targets_include_text (targets, n_targets) ||
	    e_targets_include_html (targets, n_targets)) {
		if (composer->priv->last_signal_was_paste_primary) {
			e_content_editor_paste_primary (cnt_editor);
		} else
			e_content_editor_paste (cnt_editor);
		return;
	}

	if (composer->priv->last_signal_was_paste_primary) {
		e_content_editor_paste_primary (cnt_editor);
	} else
		e_content_editor_paste (cnt_editor);
```

This looks like it wants to send the paste to the content editor only if the targets include text or html, but if the check fails it runs the same code regardless. The entire first part is superfluous.

So I can see at least two ways this code can loop forever:

- The clipboard doesn't include any compatible targets.
- The clipboard contains either text or html targets, but the content is empty.

> Do you mean the strings should be “Calendar” and “Calendar %s with server-side scheduling”?

Almost. Imagine you are translating that text. When it's split, it's bad. These are simple, thus a nice win. Just have two of them. I said "almost", because the `%s` in the later string is not meant to be there, if should be just:

```c
   if (supports_scheduling)
      g_string_append (type_info, _("Calendar with server-side scheduling"));
   else
      g_string_append (type_info, _("Calendar"));
```

I'm wondering of the wording. The calendar editor calls the option "Server handles meeting invitations". I cannot think of a good alternative here. Using similar words will help to match the option with the text for the users, I guess.
